   <exercise xml:id="ex-VVF-verify-unit">
      <statement>
         <p>
            Verify that the parameterization <m>\vr_1(s)</m> of the curve <m>C</m> in <xref ref="ex-VVF-find-arclength-fn"/> has unit speed.
         </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
         <p>
            If we are diligent and persistent with our calculations, we can show that <m>\vecmag{\vr_{1}'}=1</m>:
            <md>
            <mrow> \vr_{1}' =\amp \left\langle 2(-2+\sqrt{4+s})\frac{1/2}{\sqrt{4+s}} \right., </mrow>
            <mrow>  \amp \quad \quad   \left.  \frac{8}{3}\left(\frac{3}{2}\left(-2+\sqrt{4+s}\right)^{1/2}\left(\frac{1/2}{\sqrt{4+s}}\right)\right) ,  4 \frac{1/2}{\sqrt{4+s}} \right\rangle </mrow>
            <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{4+s}} \left\langle -2+\sqrt{4+s},2\sqrt{-2+\sqrt{4+s}},2 \right\rangle </mrow>
            <mrow> \vecmag{\vr_{1}'} =\amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{4+s}} \sqrt{\left( \left(-2+\sqrt{4+s}\right)^2+\left(2\sqrt{-2+\sqrt{4+s}}\right)^2+(2)^2 \right)} </mrow>
            <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{4+s}} \sqrt{\left( (-2+\sqrt{4+s})+2\right)^2}  </mrow>
            <mrow> =\amp \sqrt{\frac{4+s}{4+s}} = 1</mrow>
            </md>
         </p>
      </solution>
   </exercise>

   <exercise xml:id="ex-VVF-arclength-fn">
   <statement> 
      <p>
         We can adapt the arc length formula to curves in 2-space that define <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m> as the following activity shows.
      </p>
      <p>
         Let <m>y = f(x)</m> define a smooth curve in 2-space. Parameterize this curve and use Equation<nbsp/><xref ref="eq_arclength"/> to show that the length of the curve defined by <m>f</m> on an interval <m>[a,b]</m> is
         <md>
            \int_a^b \sqrt{1+[f'(t)]^2} \, dt.
         </md>
      </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
         <p>
            We can parameterize <m>y=f(x)</m> on <m>[a,b]</m> by
            <m>\vr(t) = \langle t, f(t) \rangle</m> for <m>t</m> in <m>[a,b]</m>.
            Then the length of the curve defined by <m>y=f(x)</m> on <m>[a,b]</m> is
            <md>
            \int_a^b \lvert \vr'(t) \rvert \, dt =  \int_a^b \lvert \langle 1, f'(t) \rvert \, dt = \int_a^b \sqrt{1+[f'(t)]^2} \, dt
            </md>.
         </p>
      </solution>
   </exercise>

   <exercise>
      <introduction>
         <p>
            In this exercise, we will make the unit speed parameterization for the curve parameterized by <m>\vr(t)=\langle \frac{3}{2} t^2,2t^2,\frac{5}{3}t^3\rangle</m> for <m>t\in[0,a]</m>.
         </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
         <statement>
            <p>
               Calculate the speed for the parameterization <m>\vr(t)=\langle \frac{3}{2} t^2,2t^2,\frac{5}{3}t^3\rangle</m>. Factor out as large a power of <m>t</m> out of the square root as possible. 
            </p>
         </statement>
         <solution>
            <p>
               <m>\vecmag{\vv}=\sqrt{25t^2+25t^4} = 5 t \sqrt{1+t^2} </m>
            </p>
         </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
         <statement>
            <p>
               Use your speed calculation from above to compute the arc length on our curve <m>C</m> as <m>t</m> goes from 0 to <m>a</m>. Your answer should be in terms of <m>a</m>.
            </p>
         </statement>
         <hint>
            <p>
               After factoring out the power of t, you should have a nice substitution problem with <m>u=t^2+1</m>.
            </p>
         </hint>
         <solution>
            <p>
               <m>\int_0^{a} 5 t \sqrt{1+t^2} dt = \frac{5}{3}(a^2+1)^{3/2} -\frac{5}{3} </m>
            </p>
         </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
         <statement>
            <p>
               Your previous step should have created a function <m>s(a)</m> which outputs the arclength traveled on <m>C</m> for <m>t</m> from 0 to <m>a</m>. Find the inverse function, <m>a(s)</m>, that outputs the time past 0 that is needed to travel <m>s</m> along the curve. 
            </p>
         </statement>
         <solution>
            <p>
               Solving <m>s =\frac{5}{3}(a^2+1)^{3/2} -\frac{5}{3} </m> for <m>a</m> gives <m>a(s)=\sqrt{(\frac{3}{5}s+1)^{2/3}-1}</m>
            </p>
         </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
         <statement>
            <p>
               Verify that the composition of <m>\vr(a(s))</m> is a parameterization of <m>C</m> with unit speed.
            </p>
         </statement>
         <solution>
            <p>
               <m>\vr(a(s))=\langle \frac{3}{2} (\sqrt{(\frac{3}{5}s+1)^{2/3}-1})^2,2(\sqrt{(\frac{3}{5}s+1)^{2/3}-1})^2,\frac{5}{3}(\sqrt{(\frac{3}{5}s+1)^{2/3}-1})^3\rangle</m> which will give <m>\vecmag{\vv}=1</m>
            </p>
         </solution>
      </task>
   </exercise>
   <exercise>
      <introduction>
         <p>
            In this exercise, we will look at transforming a parameterization for part of the graph of <m>y=x^2</m> to move with unit speed. While the curve is relatively simple, this conversion to a unit speed parameterization can be very difficult (or impossible even!) to write out algebraically.
         </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
         <statement>
            <p>
               Parameterize the curve given by <m>y=x^2</m> for <m>-2 \leq x \leq 2</m>
            </p>
         </statement>
         <solution>
            <p>
               <m>\vr(t)- \langle t, t^2</m> with <m>t \in [-2,2]</m>
            </p>
         </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
         <statement>
            <p>
               Compute the speed for your parameterization and set up the integral (from <xref ref="eq_arclength"/>) to calculate the arclength for the given portion of the parabola. 
            </p>
         </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
         <statement>
            <p>
               We want to compute the arclength to some value <m>a\in [-2,2]</m> so that we can find the inverse of the function <m>s(a)</m>. So we need to compute the integral with <m>a</m> as the upper bound (rather than <m>-2</m>). Write out this integral.
            </p>
            <p>
               You can either evaluate this integral with trig subsitutions and identities involving hyperbolic functions or use computer algebra system to evaluate this integral. Either way, confirm that the arclength along the curve <m>y=x^2x</m> from <m> x=-2</m> to <m>x=a</m> is given by 
               <md>s=\frac{a}{2}\sqrt{1+4a^2}+\frac{1}{4} \sinh^{-1}(2a) +\sqrt{17}+\frac{1}{4}\sinh^{-1}(4)</md>
            </p>
         </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
         <statement>
            <p>
               Write a few sentences about why you would not want to try to solve for a as a function of s.
            </p>
         </statement>
         <solution>
            <p>
               The <m>a</m> variable appears inside and outside the square root in the first term, not to mention that there is an additional <m>a</m> inside the inverse hyperbolic sine function of the second term. No amount of clever algebra or reorganizing terms will help you out of this.
            </p>
         </solution>
      </task>
   </exercise>


